{
  "doc_id": "15475",
  "text": "As discussed in the previous section, adaptive locomotor adjustments in response to environmental constraints, such as the existence of an obstacle are initiated when an obstacle is still far away. To assist such anticipatory adjustments, visual information about far space is necessary. Analyses of spatio-temporal patterns of gaze behavior during adaptive locomotion under a variety of environments, as well as under a variety of forms of locomotion, have shown that, except in a situation where very precise stepping on a footfall target is necessary [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Chapman and Hollands, 2006a,b; [CITATION_3] , fixations are directed toward far space.",
